# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dan-o-leary
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dan-o-leary/1879-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1879 throughout the world.
[src:dan-o-leary/1879-in-baseball] Inter-league playoff: Providence Grays (NL) defeat Albany Blues (NA), 2 games to 0.
[src:dan-o-leary/1880-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1880 throughout the world.
[src:dan-o-leary/1881-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1881 throughout the world.
[src:dan-o-leary/1881-in-baseball] Inter-league playoff: New York Mets (ECA) defeat Chicago (NL), 2 games to 1.
[src:dan-o-leary/1882-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1882 throughout the world.
[src:dan-o-leary/1884-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1884 throughout the world.
[src:dan-o-leary/1884-in-baseball] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:dan-o-leary/1884-in-baseball] Old Hoss Radbourn won a record 59 or 60 games (depending on the sources), a record that will almost certainly never be broken.
[src:dan-o-leary/1884-in-baseball] In addition to wins, Radbourn led the National League in games (75), games started (73), complete games (73), ERA (1.38), saves (2), strikeouts (441), and innings pitched (678.2).
[src:dan-o-leary/1884-in-baseball] The season record for pitching strikeouts (369, by Tim Keefe 1883) is broken by seven players, with Hugh Daily beating Keefe's record by 114.
[src:dan-o-leary/1884-in-baseball] To this day (as of 2020), six of the top ten strikeout seasons were accomplished in 1884 (including five of the top seven).
[src:dan-o-leary/1884-in-baseball] 1884 was the first season in which pitchers were allowed to throw overhand.
[src:dan-o-leary/at-bat] In baseball, an **at bat** (**AB**) or **time at bat** is a batter's turn batting against a pitcher.
[src:dan-o-leary/at-bat] An at bat is different from a plate appearance.
[src:dan-o-leary/at-bat] A batter is credited with a plate appearance regardless of what happens upon completion of his turn at bat, but a batter is charged with an at bat only if that plate appearance does not have one of the results enumerated below.
[src:dan-o-leary/at-bat] While at bats are used to calculate certain statistics, including batting average and slugging percentage, players can qualify for the season-ending rankings in these categories only if they accumulate 502 plate appearances during the season.
[src:dan-o-leary/at-bat] In addition, if the inning ends during an at bat (due to the third out being made by a runner caught stealing, for example), no at bat or plate appearance will result because neither were completed.
[src:dan-o-leary/at-bat] An at bat is a specific type of plate appearance in which the batter stands at the plate intending to put the ball in play and get on base.
[src:dan-o-leary/at-bat] This is why at bats, and not plate appearances, are used to calculate batting average, as plate appearances in general can result in many outcomes that do not necessarily involve putting the ball in play, and batting average specifically measures a batter's contact hitting.
[src:dan-o-leary/at-bat] Pete Rose had 14,053 career at bats, the all-time major league and National League record.
[src:dan-o-leary/at-bat] The American League record is held by Carl Yastrzemski, whose 11,988 career at bats were all in the AL.
[src:dan-o-leary/at-bat] The single season record is held by Jimmy Rollins, who had 716 at bats in 2007.
[src:dan-o-leary/at-bat] Willie Wilson, Ichiro Suzuki and Juan Samuel also had more than 700 at bats in a season.
[src:dan-o-leary/at-bat] 14 players share the single game record of 11 at bats in a single game, all of which were extra inning games.
[src:dan-o-leary/at-bat] In games of 9 innings or fewer, the record is 7 at bats and has occurred more than 200 times.
[src:dan-o-leary/at-bat] The team record for most at bats in a single season is 5,781 by the 1997 Boston Red Sox.
[src:dan-o-leary/at-bat] "At bat", "up", "up at bat", and "at the plate" are all phrases describing a batter who is facing the pitcher.
[src:dan-o-leary/at-bat] Just because a player is described as being "at bat" in this sense, he will not necessarily be given an at bat in his statistics; the phrase actually signifies a plate appearance (assuming it is eventually completed).
[src:dan-o-leary/at-bat] This ambiguous terminology is usually clarified by context.
[src:dan-o-leary/at-bat] To refer explicitly to a statistical "at bat", the term "official at bat" is sometimes used.
[src:dan-o-leary/at-bat] Official Baseball Rule 5.06(c) provides that "[a] batter has legally completed his *time at bat* when he is put out or becomes a runner" (emphasis added).
[src:dan-o-leary/at-bat] The "time at bat" defined in this rule is more commonly referred to as a plate appearance, and the playing rules (Rules 1 through 8) uses the phrase "time at bat" in this sense.
[src:dan-o-leary/at-bat] In contrast, the scoring rules use the phrase "time at bat" to refer to the statistic **at bat**, defined in Rule 9.02(a)(1), but sometimes uses the phrase "official time at bat" or refers back to Rule 9.02(a)(1) when mentioning the statistic.
[src:dan-o-leary/baseball-reference] Founder Sean Forman began developing the website while working on his Ph.D. dissertation in applied math and computational science at the University of Iowa.
[src:dan-o-leary/baseball-reference] While writing his dissertation, he had also been writing articles on and blogging about sabermetrics.
[src:dan-o-leary/baseball-reference] Forman's database was originally built from the *Total Baseball* series of baseball encyclopedias.
[src:dan-o-leary/baseball-reference] The website went online in April 2000, after first being launched in February 2000 as part of the website for the *Big Bad Baseball Annual*.
[src:dan-o-leary/baseball-reference] It was originally built as a web interface to the Lahman Baseball Database, though it now employs a variety of data sources.
[src:dan-o-leary/baseball-reference] In 2004, Forman founded Sports Reference.
[src:dan-o-leary/baseball-reference] Sports Reference is a website that came out of the Baseball Reference website.
[src:dan-o-leary/baseball-reference] The company was incorporated as Sports Reference, LLC in 2007.
[src:dan-o-leary/baseball-reference] In 2006, Forman left his job as a math professor at Saint Joseph's University to focus on Baseball Reference full-time.
[src:dan-o-leary/baseball-reference] In February 2009, Fantasy Sports Ventures took a minority stake in Sports Reference, for a "low seven-figure sum".
[src:dan-o-leary/baseball-reference] In late April 2021, the site changed a number of identifying names, "discontinuing the use of nicknames that are racially or ethnically influenced" and "names based upon a player's disability", such as Chief Bender and Dummy Hoy, who are now listed as Charles Bender and Billy Hoy, respectively.
[src:dan-o-leary/baseball-reference] To compare ballplayers to one-another it offers "Black Ink" and "Gray Ink" tests, which tally a player's dominance and overall productivity against his peers.
[src:dan-o-leary/baseball-reference] In 2012, it began to offer Jay Jaffe's Jaffe Wins Above Replacement Score (JAWS) statistic for comparing players of different eras against each other by weighing their performance in the prime as well as their entire career.
[src:dan-o-leary/baseball-reference] Baseball Reference began including its version of Wins Above Replacement (WAR) in 2010.
[src:dan-o-leary/baseball-reference] Its version determining a player's value differs slightly from other baseball statistics websites, including FanGraphs and Baseball Prospectus.
[src:dan-o-leary/baseball-reference] Baseball Reference has its own baseball encyclopedia, a wiki called "Baseball Reference Bullpen", which can be edited by anyone and is modeled after Wikipedia.
[src:dan-o-leary/baseball-reference] As of November 2025, the Bullpen contains more than 123,000 articles.
[src:dan-o-leary/dan-o-leary] O'Leary died in Chicago at the age of 65, and was buried at Mount Carmel Cemetery in Hillside, Illinois.
